column5: Average Fiscal income within a given percentile group. Fiscal income is defined as the sum of all income items reported on income tax returns, before any deduction. It includes labour income, capital income and mixed income. The concept of fiscal income varies with national tax legislations, so in order to make international comparisons it is preferable to use the concept of national income. The population is comprised of individuals over age 20. The base unit is the individual (rather than the household). This is equivalent to assuming no sharing of resources within couples.

column35: The beta coefficient corresponds to the inverted Pareto-Lorenz coefficient. It is equal to mean income over percentile <percentile>. A coefficient b=2=200% for an income level 100 000 EUR means that the average income above 100 000 EUR is 200 000 EUR, a coefficient of 3 or 300% at income level 1 000 000 EUR means that the average income level above 1 000 000 EUR in a given population is 3 000 000 EUR.

column5: Adults are: until 1969, individuals aged 15+; from 1970, tax returns (individuals aged 15+ plus those individuals below 15 years old who also file a tax return). Excludes capital gains. Tax units are: individuals aged 15+ minus married females until 1968; from 1970, tax returns (individuals aged 15+ plus those individuals below 15 years old who also file a tax return). Excludes capital gains.

column23: 1987-1995: based on the evolution of the tax value of single-family homes + agricultural properties (i.e., the 2 main categories of households' real estate). Before 1987: based on evolution of Olesen 2009 series. We checked that this gives results consistent with house price indices: housing slump from 1979 to 1982; then boom from 1982 to 1986; then slump from 1986 to 1995; then gradual increase through to 2004; then huge boom from mid-2004 to mid-2006 then slump.
